Mountain (Pennsylvania)|Blue Mountain]]\n|mile=71.68\n|tunnel=[[Lehigh Tunnel]]\n}}\n{{PAint|old|name\n|county=Carbon\n|cspan=4\n|location=Franklin Township\n|ctdab=Carbon\n|mile=75.73\n|old=34\n|exit=74\n|name=[[Mahoning Township, Carbon County, Pennsylvania|Mahoning Valley]]\n|road={{jct|state=PA|US|209|city1=Stroudsburg|city2=Lehighton}}\n|notes=Access to [[The Poconos]]\n}}\n{{PAint|old|name\n|location=Penn Forest Township\n|lspan=2\n|mile=86.62\n|place=Hickory Run Service Plaza\n}}\n{{PAint|old|name\n|mile=87.39\n|old=\u2013\n|exit=87\n|type=etc\n|name=\n|road={{jct|state=PA|PA|903|city1=Jim Thorpe|city2=Lake Harmony}}\n|notes=[[E-ZPass]]-only interchange\n}}\n{{PAint|old|name\n|location=Kidder Township\n|mile=94.82\n|old=35\n|exit=95\n|name=Pocono\n|road={{jct|state=PA|I|80|PA|940|city1=Hazleton|city2=Mount Pocono}}\n|notes=Exit 277 on I-80\n}}\n{{PAint|old|name\n|county=Luzerne\n|cspan=3\n|location=Bear Creek Township\n|mile=105.85\n|old=36\n|exit=105\n|name=Wilkes-Barre\n|road={{jct|state=PA|PA|115|city1=Wilkes-Barre|location2=[[Bear Creek Township, Luzerne County, Pennsylvania|Bear Creek]]}}\n}}\n{{PAint|old|name\n|location=Pittston Township\n|lspan=2\n|mile=113.42\n|place=[[Wyoming Valley]] Toll Plaza (north end of ticket system)\n}}\n{{PAint|old|name\n|mile=115.17\n|old=37\n|exit=115\n|name={{nowrap|Wyoming Valley}}\n|road={{jct|state=PA|PA|315|to2=to|I|81|city1=Pittston|city2=Scranton}}\n}}\n{{PAint|old|name\n|county=Lackawanna\n|cspan=4\n|location=Taylor\n|lspan=2\n|mile=121.61\n|type=etc\n|place=Keyser Avenue Mainline Toll Plaza (toll-by-plate or [[E-ZPass]])\n}}\n{{PAint|old|name\n|mile=122.36\n|old=38\n|exit=122\n|name=Keyser Avenue\n|road=[[Old Forge, Lackawanna County, Pennsylvania|Old Forge]], [[Taylor, Pennsylvania|Taylor]]\n|notes=Access via Keyser Avenue\n}}\n{{PAint|old|name\n|location=Clarks Summit\n|lspan=2\n|mile=131.20\n|type=etc\n|place=Clarks Summit Mainline Toll Plaza (toll-by-plate or [[E-ZPass]])\n}}\n{{PAint|old|name\n|mile=131.37\n|old=39\n|exit=131\n|name=Clarks Summit\n|road={{jct|state=PA|I|81|US|11|US|6|city1=Scranton|city2=Clarks Summit|location3=[[Binghamton, NY|Binghamton]]|city4=Wilkes-Barre|I|84|I|380|to4=yes}}\n|notes=Exit 194 on I-81\n}}\n{{jctbtm|col=9|keys=incomplete,etc,trans}}\n\n==See also==\n*{{Portal-inline|U.S. Roads}}\n*{{Portal-inline|Pennsylvania}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Interstate 476}}\n{{Attached KML|display=title,inline}}\n* [http://www.paturnpike.com/ Official Pennsylvania Turnpike website]\n\n{{I-76 aux}}\n{{I-80 aux}}\n{{I-95 aux}}\n{{Pennsylvania Turnpike Commission}}\n\n{{Good article}}\n\n[[Category:Interstate Highways in Pennsylvania|76-4]]\n[[Category:Delaware Valley]]\n[[Category:Lehigh Valley]]\n[[Category:Auxiliary Interstate Highways|76-4]]\n[[Category:Toll roads in Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Tolled sections of Interstate Highways]]\n[[Category:Interstate 76 (Ohio\u2013New Jersey)|4]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Delaware County, Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Montgomery County, Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Bucks County, Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Lehigh County, Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Carbon County, Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Luzerne County, Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Lackawanna County, Pennsylvania]]\n", "name_user": "Sicklemoon", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eMid-County Expressway, the \"Blue Route\":Added attribution for the sculptures at Exit 13 and title of original funding project", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Interstate_476"}
{"title_page": "Azerbaijan\u2013Iran border", "text_new": "[[File:Azerbaijan 1995 CIA map.jpg|thumb|right|Map of Azerbaijan, with Iran to the south]]\nThe '''Azerbaijan\u2013Iran border''' is 689 km (428 m) in length and consists of two non-contiguous sections separated by the [[Armenia\u2013Iran border]].<ref>{{cite |url= https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/geos/ir.html|title=CIA World Factbook - Iran|accessdate= 6 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Description==\n===Western (Nakchivan) section===\nThe border starts in the north-west at the tripoint with Turkey on the [[Aras river]], continuing along this river south-eastwards, through the Aras reservoir (created by the [[Aras Dam]]) and down to the western Armenian tripoint.\n===Eastern section===\nThe border starts in the west at the eastern Armenian tripoint on the Aras river, and then follows this river as it flows north-eastwards. The border leaves the river at a point south of [[B\u0259hramt\u0259p\u0259]], turning sharply south-eastwards and proceeding across the [[Mugan plain]] to the [[Bolgar chay (river)|Bolgarchay river]]. The border then follows this river south forming a broad S-shape. The river ends near [[Yard\u0131ml\u0131]], with the border then curving south-eastwards, proceeding overland in that direction through the [[Talysh Mountains]], then turning east along the [[Astarachay|Astarachay river]], following its course out to the [[Caspian Sea]].\n\n==History== \nDuring the 19th century the Caucasus region was contested between the declining [[Ottoman Empire]], [[Qajar Iran|Persia]] and [[Russia]], which was expanding southwards.<ref name=\"IBS025\">{{cite |url= https://fall.fsulawrc.com/collection/LimitsinSeas/IBS025.pdf|title=International Boundary Study No. 25 \u2013 Iran-USSR Boundary |date=28 February 1978|access-date=9 April 2020}}</ref> By the [[Russo-Persian War (1804\u20131813)]] and the subsequent [[Treaty of Gulistan]], Russia acquired the bulk of what is now Azerbaijan and parts of Armenia; a border was drawn which is the modern border between Iran and Azerbaijan (excluding the Nakhichevan section) and Iran and Armenia.<ref name=\"IBS025\"/><ref>John F. Baddeley, \"The Russian Conquest of the Caucasus\", Longman, Green and Co., London: 1908, p. 90</ref><ref name=\"CIA-1951\">{{cite |url= https://www.cia.gov/library/readingroom/docs/CIA-RDP79-00976A000200010003-4.pdf|title=USSR-Iran Boundary |date=February 1951|access-date=9 April 2020}}</ref> Following the [[Russo-Persian War (1826\u20131828)]] and the [[Treaty of Turkmenchay]] Persia was forced to cede Nakhchivan and the rest of Armenia to Russia; the Aras was extended as the border up to the Ottoman tripoint, thus finalising what would become the Azerbaijan-Iran border.<ref name=\"IBS025\"/><ref>Gavin R.G. Hambly, in ''The Cambridge History of Iran'', ed. William Bayne Fisher (Cambridge University Press, 1991), pp. 145-146</ref><ref name=\"CIA-1951\"/>\n\nDuring the [[First World War]] Russian Communists staged a successful [[Russian Revolution|revolution]] in 1917, whilst the peoples of the southern Caucasus had declared the [[Transcaucasian Democratic Federative Republic]] in 1918. Internal disagreements led to [[Democratic Republic of Georgia|Georgia]] leaving the federation in May 1918, followed shortly thereafter by [[First Republic of Armenia|Armenia]] and [[Azerbaijan Democratic Republic|Azerbaijan]]. By its very name the newly independent Azerbaijan caused tensions with Persia, as it seemed to imply a claim to Iran's [[Azerbaijan (Iran)|Azerbaijan region]].<ref>Tadeusz Swietochowski, Russia and Azerbaijan: A Borderland in Transition New York: Columbia University Press, 1995. pg 69</ref><ref name=\"I.B.Tauris\">{{cite book|last1=Atabaki|first1=Touraj|title=Azerbaijan: Ethnicity and the Struggle for Power in Iran |date=2000|publisher=I.B.Tauris|isbn=9781860645549|page=25}}</ref><ref name=\"I.B. Tauris\">{{cite book|last1=Dekmejian|first1=R. Hrair|last2=Simonian|first2=Hovann H.|title=Troubled Waters: The Geopolitics of the Caspian Region|date=2003|publisher=I.B. Tauris|isbn=978-1860649226|page=60|url=https://books.google.com/?id=4_jdnke35AgC&dq=azerbaijan+name+used+1918 |quote=Until 1918, when the Musavat regime decided to name the newly independent state Azerbaijan, this designation had been used exclusively to identify the [[Iranian Azerbaijan|Iranian province of Azerbaijan]].}}</ref><ref name=\"Amsterdam University Press\">{{cite book|last1=Rezvani|first1=Babak|title=Ethno-territorial conflict and coexistence in the caucasus, Central Asia and Fereydan: academisch proefschrift|date=2014|publisher=Amsterdam University Press|location=Amsterdam|isbn=978-9048519286 |page=356|quote=The region to the north of the river Araxes was not called Azerbaijan prior to 1918, unlike the region in northwestern Iran that has been called since so long ago.}}</ref> In 1920 Russia's [[Red Army]] invaded Azerbaijan and Armenia, ending the independence of both, followed shortly thereafter by Georgia. All three states were incorporated into the [[Transcaucasian Socialist Federative Soviet Republic| Transcaucasian SFSR]] within the [[USSR]], before being separated in 1936. A Soviet-backed [[Azerbaijan People's Government|separatist state]] in Iranian Azerbaijan was established 1945 but was soon quashed by Iranian forces.<ref>{{citation|title=The Caucasus - An Introduction|author=Frederik Coene|publisher=Routledge|date=2009|isbn=9781135203023|series=Routledge Contemporary Russia and Eastern Europe Series|page=136|quote=As a result, the People's Republic of Azerbaijan and the Kurdish People's Republic (the Republic of Mahabad), two short-lived Soviet puppet states, were set up late in 1945...}}</ref>\n\nAn Iran-USSR border convention in 1954 made some minor adjustments along the frontier in the Mugan plain and near [[Deman]] and [[Namin, Ardabil|Namin]], to Iran's benefit.<ref name=\"IBS025\"/> On-the-ground demarcation then followed, with a final agreement being agreed upon in 1957.<ref name=\"IBS025\"/> In 1970 some further adjustments were made to the Nakhchivan section of the border following the creation of the Aras dam.<ref name=\"IBS025\"/>\n\nFollowing the collapse of the USSR in 1991 Azerbaijan gained independence and inherited its section of the Iran-USSR border. Iran quickly recognised the new state, though relations cooled over Iranian fears of Azerbaijan\u2019s potential claims to its territory as part of a '[[Greater Azerbaijan]]', with Iran championing Armenia in the [[Nagorno-Karabakh War]].<ref name=\"nichol150\">James P. Nichol. ''Diplomacy in the Former Soviet Republics'', Praeger/Greenwood, 1995, {{ISBN|0-275-95192-8}}, p. 150</ref><ref name=\"Svante\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=ff2zOZYaZx0C&pg=PA324&dq=elchibey+iran|title=Small Nations and Great Powers: A Study of Ethnopolitical Conflict in the Caucasus|first=Svante|last=Cornell|date=1 December 2000|publisher=Taylor & Francis|accessdate=28 September 2018|via=Google Books|isbn=9780203988879}}</ref> Following the was Armenia was left in control of the western-most section of the 'mainland' Azerbaijan-Iran border. Relations between Iran and Azerbaijan have improved somewhat since the accession of [[Hassan Rouhani]] in Iran.\n\n==Settlements near the border==\n[[File:Aras River with Nagorno Karabakh-Azerbaijan at Right - Iran at Left - Iranian Azerbaijan - Iran (7421349614).jpg|thumb|right|The Aras border, taken from Iran looking into Azerbaijan]]\n===Azerbaijan===\n{{div col|colwidth=20em}}\n* [[Q\u0131vraq]]\n* [[Nakhchivan (city)]]\n* [[Nehr\u0259m]]\n* [[D\u0259st\u0259]]\n* [[Julfa, Azerbaijan (city)|Julfa]]\n* [[Ordubad]]\n* [[Mincivan, Zangilan|Mincivan]]\n* [[X\u0259l\u0259fli]]\n* [[Ma\u015fanl\u0131]]\n* [[Soltanl\u0131]]\n* [[\u018fmirvarl\u0131]]\n* [[A\u015fa\u011f\u0131 Maralyan]]\n* [[C\u0259f\u0259rabad, Jabrayil|C\u0259f\u0259rabad]]\n* [[Mahmudlu, Jabrayil|Mahmudlu]]\n* [[B\u00f6y\u00fck M\u0259rcanl\u0131]]\n* [[Mehdili, Jabrayil|Mehdili]]\n* [[Qazaxlar, Fizuli|Qazaxlar]]\n* [[Horadiz]]\n* [[Mollam\u0259h\u0259rr\u0259mli]]\n* [[Arayatl\u0131]]\n* [[K\u0259rimb\u0259yli, Fizuli|K\u0259rimb\u0259yli]]\n* [[Bala B\u0259hm\u0259nli]]\n* [[Birinci Mahmudlu]]\n* [[\u018fmirzeydli]]\n* [[\u0130kinci \u015eahsev\u0259n]]\n* [[Birinci \u015eahsev\u0259n]]\n* [[A\u015fa\u011f\u0131 \u00c7\u0259m\u0259nli]]\n* [[B\u0259hramt\u0259p\u0259]]\n* [[Bil\u0259suvar]]\n* [[Zevin]]\n* [[Yard\u0131ml\u0131]]\n* [[L\u0259zran, Yardymli|L\u0259zran]]\n* [[Deman]]\n* [[Qaravulda\u015f]]\n* [[Qosmalyan]]\n* [[G\u00f6vd\u0259r\u0259]]\n* [[M\u0259scidm\u0259h\u0259ll\u0259]]\n* [[Supariba\u011f]]\n* [[Astara, Azerbaijan|Astara]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Iran==\n{{div col|colwidth=20em}}\n* [[Shoja, East Azerbaijan|Shoja]]\n* [[Jolfa, Iran (city)|Jolfa]]\n* [[Chenaqchi]]\n* [[Qareh Qabaq-e Sofla]]\n* [[Chalmeh Kandi]]\n* [[Jahan Khanamlu]]\n* [[Qeshlaq-e Jahan Khanemlu]]\n* [[Qareh Quch, East Azerbaijan|Qareh Quch]] \n* [[Tatar-e Olya, East Azerbaijan|Tatar-e Olya]]\n* [[Tu Ali-ye Olya]]\n* [[Kurzeh]]\n* [[Zanbalan, East Azerbaijan|Zanbalan]]\n* [[Larijan-e Sofla]]\n* [[Eskanlou-e-Sofla]]\n* [[Mohammad Salehu]]\n* [[Gun Gowrmez]]\n* [[Khalaf Beygluy-e Sofla]]\n* [[Aslan Duz]]\n* [[Maqsudlu-ye Olya]]\n* [[Surkha Kandi]]\n* [[Hazar Kandi Qeshlaqi]]\n* [[Kasihli]]\n* [[Pirayuvatlu]]\n* [[Parya Katli]]\n* [[Parsabad]]\n* [[Qamishchu]]\n* [[Bileh Savar]]\n* [[Germi]]\n* [[Agh Bolagh, Ardabil|Agh Bolagh]]\n* [[Khvajeh Bolaghi]]\n* [[Sij, Gilan|Sij]]\n* [[Giladeh]]\n* [[Qaleh, Gilan|Qaleh]]\n* [[Astara, Iran|Astara]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Border Crossings==\nThere are crossings between \u2018mainland\u2019 Azerbaijan and Iran at Bilasuvar and Astara.<ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite |url= https://caravanistan.com/border-crossings/iran/#iran-azerbaijan-border-crossings|title=Caravanistan \u2013 Azerbaijan-Iran border crossings |access-date=9 April 2020}}</ref> Crossings between Iran and Nakchivan are at Jolfa/Julfa and Poldasht \u2013 Shahtakhti.<ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Azerbaijan-Iran relations]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{Borders of Azerbaijan}}\n{{Borders of Iran}}\n\n[[Category:Borders of Azerbaijan]]\n[[Category:Borders of Iran]]\n[[Category:International borders]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Azerbaijan 1995 CIA map.jpg|thumb|right|Map of Azerbaijan, with Iran to the south]]\nThe '''Azerbaijan\u2013Iran border''' is 689 km (428 m) in length and consists of two non-contiguous sections separated by the [[Armenia\u2013Iran border]].<ref>{{cite |url= https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/geos/ir.html|title=CIA World Factbook - Iran|accessdate= 6 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Description==\n===Western (Nakchivan) section===\nThe border starts in the north-west at the tripoint with Turkey on the [[Aras river]], continuing along this river south-eastwards, through the Aras reservoir (created by the [[Aras Dam]]) and down to the western Armenian tripoint.\n===Eastern section===\nThe border starts in the west at the eastern Armenian tripoint on the Aras river, and then follows this river as it flows north-eastwards. The border leaves the river at a point south of [[B\u0259hramt\u0259p\u0259]], turning sharply south-eastwards and proceeding across the [[Mugan plain]] to the [[Bolgar chay (river)|Bolgarchay river]]. The border then follows this river south forming a broad S-shape. The river ends near [[Yard\u0131ml\u0131]], with the border then curving south-eastwards, proceeding overland in that direction through the [[Talysh Mountains]], then turning east along the [[Astarachay|Astarachay river]], following its course out to the [[Caspian Sea]].\n\n==History== \nDuring the 19th century the Caucasus region was contested between the declining [[Ottoman Empire]], [[Qajar Iran|Persia]] and [[Russia]], which was expanding southwards.<ref name=\"IBS025\">{{cite |url= https://fall.fsulawrc.com/collection/LimitsinSeas/IBS025.pdf|title=International Boundary Study No. 25 \u2013 Iran-USSR Boundary |date=28 February 1978|access-date=9 April 2020}}</ref> By the [[Russo-Persian War (1804\u20131813)]] and the subsequent [[Treaty of Gulistan]], Russia acquired the bulk of what is now Azerbaijan and parts of Armenia; a border was drawn which is the modern border between Iran and Azerbaijan (excluding the Nakhichevan section) and Iran and Armenia.<ref name=\"IBS025\"/><ref>John F. Baddeley, \"The Russian Conquest of the Caucasus\", Longman, Green and Co., London: 1908, p. 90</ref><ref name=\"CIA-1951\">{{cite |url= https://www.cia.gov/library/readingroom/docs/CIA-RDP79-00976A000200010003-4.pdf|title=USSR-Iran Boundary |date=February 1951|access-date=9 April 2020}}</ref> Following the [[Russo-Persian War (1826\u20131828)]] and the [[Treaty of Turkmenchay]] Persia was forced to cede Nakhchivan and the rest of Armenia to Russia; the Aras was extended as the border up to the Ottoman tripoint, thus finalising what would become the Azerbaijan-Iran border.<ref name=\"IBS025\"/><ref>Gavin R.G. Hambly, in ''The Cambridge History of Iran'', ed. William Bayne Fisher (Cambridge University Press, 1991), pp. 145-146</ref><ref name=\"CIA-1951\"/>\n\nDuring the [[First World War]] Russian Communists staged a successful [[Russian Revolution|revolution]] in 1917, whilst the peoples of the southern Caucasus had declared the [[Transcaucasian Democratic Federative Republic]] in 1918. Internal disagreements led to [[Democratic Republic of Georgia|Georgia]] leaving the federation in May 1918, followed shortly thereafter by [[First Republic of Armenia|Armenia]] and [[Azerbaijan Democratic Republic|Azerbaijan]]. By its very name the newly independent Azerbaijan caused tensions with Persia, as it seemed to imply a claim to Iran's [[Azerbaijan (Iran)|Azerbaijan region]].<ref>Tadeusz Swietochowski, Russia and Azerbaijan: A Borderland in Transition New York: Columbia University Press, 1995. pg 69</ref><ref name=\"I.B.Tauris\">{{cite book|last1=Atabaki|first1=Touraj|title=Azerbaijan: Ethnicity and the Struggle for Power in Iran |date=2000|publisher=I.B.Tauris|isbn=9781860645549|page=25}}</ref><ref name=\"I.B. Tauris\">{{cite book|last1=Dekmejian|first1=R. Hrair|last2=Simonian|first2=Hovann H.|title=Troubled Waters: The Geopolitics of the Caspian Region|date=2003|publisher=I.B. Tauris|isbn=978-1860649226|page=60|url=https://books.google.com/?id=4_jdnke35AgC&dq=azerbaijan+name+used+1918 |quote=Until 1918, when the Musavat regime decided to name the newly independent state Azerbaijan, this designation had been used exclusively to identify the [[Iranian Azerbaijan|Iranian province of Azerbaijan]].}}</ref><ref name=\"Amsterdam University Press\">{{cite book|last1=Rezvani|first1=Babak|title=Ethno-territorial conflict and coexistence in the caucasus, Central Asia and Fereydan: academisch proefschrift|date=2014|publisher=Amsterdam University Press|location=Amsterdam|isbn=978-9048519286 |page=356|quote=The region to the north of the river Araxes was not called Azerbaijan prior to 1918, unlike the region in northwestern Iran that has been called since so long ago.}}</ref> In 1920 Russia's [[Red Army]] invaded Azerbaijan and Armenia, ending the independence of both, followed shortly thereafter by Georgia. All three states were incorporated into the [[Transcaucasian Socialist Federative Soviet Republic| Transcaucasian SFSR]] within the [[USSR]], before being separated in 1936. A Soviet-backed [[Azerbaijan People's Government|separatist state]] in Iranian Azerbaijan was established 1945 but was soon quashed by Iranian forces.<ref>{{citation|title=The Caucasus - An Introduction|author=Frederik Coene|publisher=Routledge|date=2009|isbn=9781135203023|series=Routledge Contemporary Russia and Eastern Europe Series|page=136|quote=As a result, the People's Republic of Azerbaijan and the Kurdish People's Republic (the Republic of Mahabad), two short-lived Soviet puppet states, were set up late in 1945...}}</ref>\n\nAn Iran-USSR border convention in 1954 made some minor adjustments along the frontier in the Mugan plain and near [[Deman]] and [[Namin, Ardabil|Namin]], to Iran's benefit.<ref name=\"IBS025\"/> On-the-ground demarcation then followed, with a final agreement being agreed upon in 1957.<ref name=\"IBS025\"/> In 1970 some further adjustments were made to the Nakhchivan section of the border following the creation of the Aras dam.<ref name=\"IBS025\"/>\n\nFollowing the collapse of the USSR in 1991 Azerbaijan gained independence and inherited its section of the Iran-USSR border. Iran quickly recognised the new state, though relations cooled over Iranian fears of Azerbaijan\u2019s potential claims to its territory as part of a '[[Greater Azerbaijan]]', with Iran championing Armenia in the [[Nagorno-Karabakh War]].<ref name=\"nichol150\">James P. Nichol. ''Diplomacy in the Former Soviet Republics'', Praeger/Greenwood, 1995, {{ISBN|0-275-95192-8}}, p. 150</ref><ref name=\"Svante\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=ff2zOZYaZx0C&pg=PA324&dq=elchibey+iran|title=Small Nations and Great Powers: A Study of Ethnopolitical Conflict in the Caucasus|first=Svante|last=Cornell|date=1 December 2000|publisher=Taylor & Francis|accessdate=28 September 2018|via=Google Books|isbn=9780203988879}}</ref> Following the was Armenia was left in control of the western-most section of the 'mainland' Azerbaijan-Iran border. Relations between Iran and Azerbaijan have improved somewhat since the accession of [[Hassan Rouhani]] in Iran.\n\n==Settlements near the border==\n[[File:Aras River with Nagorno Karabakh-Azerbaijan at Right - Iran at Left - Iranian Azerbaijan - Iran (7421349614).jpg|thumb|right|The Aras border, taken from Iran looking into Azerbaijan]]\n===Azerbaijan===\n{{div col|colwidth=20em}}\n* [[Q\u0131vraq]]\n* [[Nakhchivan (city)]]\n* [[Nehr\u0259m]]\n* [[D\u0259st\u0259]]\n* [[Julfa, Azerbaijan (city)|Julfa]]\n* [[Ordubad]]\n* [[Mincivan, Zangilan|Mincivan]]\n* [[X\u0259l\u0259fli]]\n* [[Ma\u015fanl\u0131]]\n* [[Soltanl\u0131]]\n* [[\u018fmirvarl\u0131]]\n* [[A\u015fa\u011f\u0131 Maralyan]]\n* [[C\u0259f\u0259rabad, Jabrayil|C\u0259f\u0259rabad]]\n* [[Mahmudlu,Jabrayil|Mahmudlu]]\n* [[B\u00f6y\u00fck M\u0259rcanl\u0131]]\n* [[Mehdili, Jabrayil|Mehdili]]\n* [[Qazaxlar, Fizuli|Qazaxlar]]\n* [[Horadiz]]\n* [[Mollam\u0259h\u0259rr\u0259mli]]\n* [[Arayatl\u0131]]\n* [[K\u0259rimb\u0259yli, Fizuli|K\u0259rimb\u0259yli]]\n* [[Bala B\u0259hm\u0259nli]]\n* [[Birinci Mahmudlu]]\n* [[\u018fmirzeydli]]\n* [[\u0130kinci \u015eahsev\u0259n]]\n* [[Birinci \u015eahsev\u0259n]]\n* [[A\u015fa\u011f\u0131 \u00c7\u0259m\u0259nli]]\n* [[B\u0259hramt\u0259p\u0259]]\n* [[Bil\u0259suvar]]\n* [[Zevin]]\n* [[Yard\u0131ml\u0131]]\n* [[L\u0259zran, Yardymli|L\u0259zran]]\n* [[Deman]]\n* [[Qaravulda\u015f]]\n* [[Qosmalyan]]\n* [[G\u00f6vd\u0259r\u0259]]\n* [[M\u0259scidm\u0259h\u0259ll\u0259]]\n* [[Supariba\u011f]]\n* [[Astara, Azerbaijan|Astara]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Iran==\n{{div col|colwidth=20em}}\n* [[Shoja, East Azerbaijan|Shoja]]\n* [[Jolfa, Iran (city)|Jolfa]]\n* [[Chenaqchi]]\n* [[Qareh Qabaq-e Sofla]]\n* [[Chalmeh Kandi]]\n* [[Jahan Khanamlu]]\n* [[Qeshlaq-e Jahan Khanemlu]]\n* [[Qareh Quch, East Azerbaijan|Qareh Quch]] \n* [[Tatar-e Olya, East Azerbaijan|Tatar-e Olya]]\n* [[Tu Ali-ye Olya]]\n* [[Kurzeh]]\n* [[Zanbalan, East Azerbaijan|Zanbalan]]\n* [[Larijan-e Sofla]]\n* [[Eskanlou-e-Sofla]]\n* [[Mohammad Salehu]]\n* [[Gun Gowrmez]]\n* [[Khalaf Beygluy-e Sofla]]\n* [[Aslan Duz]]\n* [[Maqsudlu-ye Olya]]\n* [[Surkha Kandi]]\n* [[Hazar Kandi Qeshlaqi]]\n* [[Kasihli]]\n* [[Pirayuvatlu]]\n* [[Parya Katli]]\n* [[Parsabad]]\n* [[Qamishchu]]\n* [[Bileh Savar]]\n* [[Germi]]\n* [[Agh Bolagh, Ardabil|Agh Bolagh]]\n* [[Khvajeh Bolaghi]]\n* [[Sij, Gilan|Sij]]\n* [[Giladeh]]\n* [[Qaleh, Gilan|Qaleh]]\n* [[Astara, Iran|Astara]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Border Crossings==\nThere are crossings between \u2018mainland\u2019 Azerbaijan and Iran at Bilasuvar and Astara.<ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite |url= https://caravanistan.com/border-crossings/iran/#iran-azerbaijan-border-crossings|title=Caravanistan \u2013 Azerbaijan-Iran border crossings |access-date=9 April 2020}}</ref> Crossings between Iran and Nakchivan are at Jolfa/Julfa and Poldasht \u2013 Shahtakhti.<ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Azerbaijan-Iran relations]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{Borders of Azerbaijan}}\n{{Borders of Iran}}\n\n[[Category:Borders of Azerbaijan]]\n[[Category:Borders of Iran]]\n[[Category:International borders]]\n", "name_user": "WisDom-UK", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSettlements near the border", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Azerbaijan%E2%80%93Iran_border"}
